98
00:05:42.570 --> 00:05:44.570
I would not draw them.

99
00:05:44.570 --> 00:05:46.200
I would have my bond.

100
00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:50.930
How shalt thou hope formercy, rendering none?

101
00:05:50.930 --> 00:05:52.930
What judgment shall Idread, doing no wrong?

102
00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:54.230
No wrong!

103
00:05:54.230 --> 00:05:59.300
You have amongst you manya purchased slave,

104
00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:02.230
which, like your asses andyour dogs and mules,

105
00:06:02.230 --> 00:06:05.300
you use in abject and inslavish parts

106
00:06:05.300 --> 00:06:06.930
because you bought them.

107
00:06:06.930 --> 00:06:08.400
Shall I say to you, "Letthem be free.

108
00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:10.300
"Marry them to your heirs.

109
00:06:10.300 --> 00:06:12.270
"Why sweat they underburdens?

110
00:06:12.270 --> 00:06:14.230
"Let their beds be made assoft as yours.

111
00:06:14.230 --> 00:06:17.430
Let their palates beseasoned with such viands?"

112
00:06:17.430 --> 00:06:21.000
You will answer, "Theslaves are ours."

113
00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:22.300
So do I answer you.

114
00:06:22.300 --> 00:06:29.070
The pound of flesh which Idemand of him is dearly bought.

115
00:06:29.070 --> 00:06:33.000
'Tis mine, and I will haveit.

116
00:06:33.430 --> 00:06:37.700
If you deny me, fie uponyour law.

117
00:06:37.700 --> 00:06:41.470
There is no force in thedecrees of Venice.

118
00:06:41.470 --> 00:06:45.030
I stand for judgment.

119
00:06:45.030 --> 00:06:47.400
Answer!

120
00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:49.030
Shall I have it?

121
00:06:49.030 --> 00:06:53.570
Upon my power, I maydismiss this court,

122
00:06:53.570 --> 00:06:56.600
unless Bellario, a learneddoctor

123
00:06:56.600 --> 00:06:58.670
whom I have sent for todetermine this,

124
00:06:58.670 --> 00:07:00.330
come here today.

125
00:07:00.330 --> 00:07:01.930
My lord, here stayswithout

126
00:07:01.930 --> 00:07:03.670
a messenger with lettersfrom the doctor,

127
00:07:03.670 --> 00:07:04.930
new come from Padua.

128
00:07:04.930 --> 00:07:06.170
Bring us the letters.

129
00:07:06.170 --> 00:07:07.530
Call the messenger.

130
00:07:07.530 --> 00:07:09.530
Good cheer, Antonio.

131
00:07:09.530 --> 00:07:11.030
What, man, courage yet.

132
00:07:11.030 --> 00:07:13.830
The Jew shall have my flesh,blood, bones, and all,

133
00:07:13.830 --> 00:07:16.970
ere thou shalt lose for meone drop of blood.

134
00:07:16.970 --> 00:07:19.930
I am a tainted wether of theflock, meetest for death.

135
00:07:19.930 --> 00:07:22.830
The weakest kind of fruitdrops earliest to the ground,

136
00:07:22.830 --> 00:07:24.570
and so let me.

137
00:07:24.570 --> 00:07:26.300
You cannot better beemployed, Bessanio,

138
00:07:26.300 --> 00:07:29.430
than to live still, andwrite mine epitaph.

139
00:07:41.130 --> 00:07:44.430
Come you from Padua, fromBellario?

140
00:07:44.430 --> 00:07:46.070
From both, my lord.

141
00:07:46.070 --> 00:07:48.230
Bellario greets yourgrace.

142
00:07:54.630 --> 00:07:57.030
Why dost thou whet thyknife so earnestly?

143
00:07:57.030 --> 00:08:01.000
To cut the forfeiture fromthat bankrupt there.

144
00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.530
Not on thy sole, but onthy soul, harsh Jew,

145
00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:07.370
thou mak'st thy knifekeen.

146
00:08:07.370 --> 00:08:09.930
But no metal can-- no, notthe hangman's axe--

147
00:08:09.930 --> 00:08:12.670
bear half the keenness ofthy sharp envy.

148
00:08:12.670 --> 00:08:15.130
Can no prayers piercethee?

149
00:08:15.130 --> 00:08:18.900
No, none that thou hastwit enough to make.

150
00:08:18.900 --> 00:08:21.830
Oh, be thou damned,inexecrable dog.

151
00:08:21.830 --> 00:08:26.700
And for thy life, letjustice be accused.

152
00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:28.530
Thou almost mak'st mewaver in my faith

153
00:08:28.530 --> 00:08:30.470
to hold opinion withPythagoras

154
00:08:30.470 --> 00:08:32.570
that souls of animalsinfuse themselves

155
00:08:32.570 --> 00:08:34.130
into the trunks of men.

156
00:08:34.130 --> 00:08:39.230
Thy currish spirit governeda wolf, who, hang'd forhuman slaughter,

157
00:08:39.230 --> 00:08:41.870
even from the gallows didhis fell soul fleet,

158
00:08:41.870 --> 00:08:44.000
and while thou layest inthy unhallowed dam,

159
00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:45.670
infused itself in thee.

160
00:08:45.670 --> 00:08:50.470
For thy desires arewolvish, bloody, starved,and ravenous.

161
00:08:50.470 --> 00:08:55.500
Till thou canst rail theseal from off my bond,

162
00:08:55.500 --> 00:08:58.270
thou but offend'st thylungs to speak so loud.

163
00:08:58.270 --> 00:09:00.630
Repair thy wit, goodyouth,

164
00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:02.700
or it will fall tocureless ruin.

165
00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:04.800
I stand here for law.

166
00:09:04.800 --> 00:09:07.370
This letter from Bellariodoth commend

167
00:09:07.370 --> 00:09:09.470
a young and learned doctorto our court.

168
00:09:09.470 --> 00:09:10.870
Where is he?

169
00:09:10.870 --> 00:09:12.200
He attendeth here hard by

170
00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:14.100
