171
00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:16.070
With all my heart.

172
00:09:16.070 --> 00:09:17.630
Some three or four of you

173
00:09:17.630 --> 00:09:19.930
go give him courteousconduct to this place.

174
00:09:19.930 --> 00:09:22.770
Meantime, the court shallhear Bellario's letter.

175
00:09:22.770 --> 00:09:25.300
"Your grace shallunderstand

176
00:09:25.300 --> 00:09:27.770
"that at the receipt of yourletter, I am very sick,

177
00:09:27.770 --> 00:09:31.730
"but in the instant thatyour messenger came,

178
00:09:31.730 --> 00:09:34.830
"in loving visitation was withme a young doctor of Rome.

179
00:09:34.830 --> 00:09:36.670
"His name is Balthasar.

180
00:09:36.670 --> 00:09:39.800
"I acquainted him with thecause in controversy

181
00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:42.200
"between the Jew andAntonio the merchant.

182
00:09:42.200 --> 00:09:44.470
"We turned o'er many bookstogether.

183
00:09:44.470 --> 00:09:46.330
"He is furnished with myopinion,

184
00:09:46.330 --> 00:09:48.930
"which, bettered with hisown learning--

185
00:09:48.930 --> 00:09:51.670
"the greatness whereof Icannot enough commend--

186
00:09:51.670 --> 00:09:53.830
"comes with him at myimportunity

187
00:09:53.830 --> 00:09:57.030
"to fill up your grace'srequest in my stead.

188
00:09:57.030 --> 00:10:00.930
"I beseech you let his lackof years be no impediment

189
00:10:00.930 --> 00:10:03.670
"to let him lack areverend estimation,

190
00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:09.100
"for I never knew so younga body with so old a head.

191
00:10:09.100 --> 00:10:10.800
"I leave him to yourgracious acceptance,

192
00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:13.930
whose trial shall betterpublish his commendation."

193
00:10:13.930 --> 00:10:17.900
You hear the learnedBellario what he writes.

194
00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:21.070
And here, I take it, isthe doctor come.

195
00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:24.970
Give me your hand.

196
00:10:27.100 --> 00:10:29.130
Came you from oldBellario?

197
00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:30.300
I did, my lord.

198
00:10:30.300 --> 00:10:33.730
You are welcome; take yourplace.

199
00:10:38.370 --> 00:10:42.000
Are you acquainted withthe difference

200
00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.330
that holds the presentquestion in the court?

201
00:10:44.330 --> 00:10:46.930
I am informed throughly ofthe cause.

202
00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:53.700
Which is the merchant hereand which the Jew?

203
00:10:53.700 --> 00:10:56.570
Antonio and old Shylock,both stand forth.

204
00:11:00.100 --> 00:11:01.400
Is your name Shylock?

205
00:11:01.400 --> 00:11:03.270
Shylock is my name.

206
00:11:03.270 --> 00:11:06.970
Of a strange nature isthat suit you follow,

207
00:11:06.970 --> 00:11:10.330
yet in such rule that theVenetian law

208
00:11:10.330 --> 00:11:12.770
cannot impugn you as youdo proceed.

209
00:11:12.770 --> 00:11:15.630
You stand within hisdanger, do you not?

210
00:11:15.630 --> 00:11:18.170
Ay, so he says.

211
00:11:18.170 --> 00:11:20.030
Do you confess the bond?

212
00:11:20.030 --> 00:11:22.200
I do.

213
00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:23.930
Then must the Jew bemerciful.

214
00:11:23.930 --> 00:11:25.270
On what compulsion must I?

215
00:11:25.270 --> 00:11:26.700
Tell me that.

216
00:11:27.970 --> 00:11:31.100
The quality of mercy isnot strained.

217
00:11:31.100 --> 00:11:33.870
It droppeth as the gentlerain from heaven

218
00:11:33.870 --> 00:11:35.400
upon the place beneath.

219
00:11:35.400 --> 00:11:39.330
It is twice blest.

220
00:11:39.330 --> 00:11:41.500
It blesseth him that givesand him that takes.

221
00:11:41.500 --> 00:11:45.430
'Tis mightiest in themightiest.

222
00:11:45.430 --> 00:11:48.100
It becomes the throned monarchbetter than his crown.

223
00:11:48.100 --> 00:11:51.530
His sceptre shows theforce of temporal power,

224
00:11:51.530 --> 00:11:54.270
the attribute to awe andmajesty,

225
00:11:54.270 --> 00:11:57.270
wherein doth sit the dreadand fear of kings.

226
00:11:57.270 --> 00:12:00.570
But mercy is above thissceptred sway.

227
00:12:00.570 --> 00:12:04.130
It is enthroned in thehearts of kings.

228
00:12:04.130 --> 00:12:07.530
It is an attribute to Godhimself.

229
00:12:07.530 --> 00:12:11.370
And earthly power doththen show likest God's

230
00:12:11.370 --> 00:12:14.370
when mercy seasonsjustice.

231
00:12:14.370 --> 00:12:18.330
Therefore, Jew, thoughjustice be thy plea,

232
00:12:18.330 --> 00:12:21.970
consider this that, in thecourse of justice,

233
00:12:21.970 --> 00:12:25.800
none of us should seesalvation.

234
00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:27.530
We do pray for mercy,

235
00:12:27.530 --> 00:12:30.530
and that same prayer dothteach us all

236
00:12:30.530 --> 00:12:33.930
to render the deeds ofmercy.

237
00:12:33.930 --> 00:12:38.000
I have spoke thus much tomitigate the justice ofthy plea.

238
00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.430
Which, if thou follow, thisstrict court of Venice

239
00:12:40.430 --> 00:12:43.530
must needs give sentence'gainst the merchant there.

240
00:12:45.770 --> 00:12:48.230
My deeds upon my head.

241
00:12:48.230 --> 00:12:54.170
I crave the law, the penaltyand forfeit of my bond.

242
00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.830
Is he not able todischarge the money?

243
00:13:00.830 --> 00:13:02.570
Yes, here.

244
00:13:02.570 --> 00:13:04.300
I tender it for him in thecourt.

245
00:13:04.300 --> 00:13:06.100
Yea, twice the sum.

246
00:13:06.100 --> 00:13:09.970
If that will not suffice,I will be bound to pay itten times o'er

247
00:13:09.970 --> 00:13:12.200
on forfeit of my hands, myhead, my heart.

248
00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:13.930
If this will not suffice,

249
00:13:13.930 --> 00:13:17.500
it must appear that malicebears down truth.

250
00:13:17.500 --> 00:13:19.530
And I beseech you,

251
00:13:19.530 --> 00:13:22.030
wrest once the law to yourauthority

252
00:13:22.030 --> 00:13:24.670
to do a great right, do alittle wrong,

253
00:13:24.670 --> 00:13:26.970
and curb this cruel devilof his will.

254
00:13:26.970 --> 00:13:28.530
It must not be.

255
00:13:28.530 --> 00:13:31.970
There is no power inVenice can alter a decreeestablished.

256
00:13:31.970 --> 00:13:34.400
'Twill be recorded for aprecedent,

257
00:13:34.400 --> 00:13:37.200
and many an error by thesame example will rushinto the state.

258
00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:38.400
It cannot be.

259
00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:39.700
A Daniel come to judgment.

260
00:13:39.700 --> 00:13:42.270
Yea, a Daniel.

261
00:13:42.270 --> 00:13:46.670
Oh, wise young judge, howI do honor thee.

262
00:13:46.670 --> 00:13:48.600
I pray you, let me lookupon the bond.

263
00:13:48.600 --> 00:13:51.000
Here 'tis, most reverenddoctor.

264
00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:52.730
Here it is.

265
00:13:52.730 --> 00:13:54.030
Shylock,

266
00:13:54.030 --> 00:13:58.200
there's thrice thy moneyoffered thee.

267
00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:03.070
An oath, an oath, I havean oath in heaven.

268
00:14:03.070 --> 00:14:06.100
Shall I lay perjury uponmy soul?

269
00:14:06.100 --> 00:14:08.330
No, not for Venice.

270
00:14:10.800 --> 00:14:12.530
Why, this bond is forfeit,

271
00:14:12.530 --> 00:14:15.870
and lawfully by this,

272
00:14:15.870 --> 00:14:18.070
the Jew may claim a poundof flesh

273
00:14:18.070 --> 00:14:22.270
to be by him cut off nearestthe merchant's heart.

274
00:14:22.270 --> 00:14:23.500
Be merciful.

275
00:14:23.500 --> 00:14:24.730
Take thrice thy money.

276
00:14:24.730 --> 00:14:26.400
Bid me tear the bond.

277
00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:28.800
When it is paid accordingto the tenor.

278
00:14:28.800 --> 00:14:32.330
It doth appear you are aworthy judge.

279
00:14:32.330 --> 00:14:33.970
You know the law.

280
00:14:33.970 --> 00:14:37.070
Your exposition hath beenmost sound.

281
00:14:37.070 --> 00:14:39.270
I charge you, by the law,

282
00:14:39.270 --> 00:14:41.600
whereof you are awell-deserving pillar,

283
00:14:41.600 --> 00:14:43.730
proceed to judgment.

284
00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:47.800
By my soul, I swear thereis no power in the tongueof man to alter me.

285
00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:49.400
I stay here on my bond.

286
00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:52.370
Most heartily, I dobeseech the court to givethe judgment.

287
00:14:52.370 --> 00:14:55.670
Why then, thus it is.

288
00:14:55.670 --> 00:14:58.100
You must prepare yourbosom for his knife.

289
00:14:58.100 --> 00:15:00.200
Oh, noble judge.

290
00:15:00.200 --> 00:15:02.100
Oh, excellent young man.

291
00:15:02.100 --> 00:15:05.270
For the intent and purposeof the law hath fullrelation to the penalty

292
00:15:05.270 --> 00:15:06.870
which here appeareth dueupon the bond.

293
00:15:06.870 --> 00:15:08.000
'Tis very true.

294
00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.400
Oh, wise and uprightjudge.

295
00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:13.300
How much more elder artthou than thy looks.

296
00:15:13.300 --> 00:15:15.370
Therefore, lay bare yourbosom.

297
00:15:15.370 --> 00:15:17.470
Ay, his breast.

298
00:15:17.470 --> 00:15:19.370
So says the bond.

299
00:15:19.370 --> 00:15:20.730
Doth it not, noble judge?

300
00:15:20.730 --> 00:15:22.300
Nearest his heart.

301
00:15:22.300 --> 00:15:23.400
Those are the very words.

302
00:15:23.400 --> 00:15:24.570
It is so.

303
00:15:24.570 --> 00:15:26.600
Are there balance here toweigh the flesh?

304
00:15:26.600 --> 00:15:28.000
I have them ready.

305
00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.570
Have by some surgeon,Shylock, on your charge,

306
00:15:30.570 --> 00:15:34.230
to stop his wounds, lesthe do bleed to death?

307
00:15:34.230 --> 00:15:35.900
Is it so nominated in thebond?

308
00:15:35.900 --> 00:15:38.400
It is not so expressed,but what of that?

309
00:15:38.400 --> 00:15:40.800
'Twere good you do so muchfor charity.

310
00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:43.500
I cannot find it.

311
00:15:43.500 --> 00:15:45.830
'Tis not in the bond.

312
00:15:45.830 --> 00:15:49.370
You, merchant, have youanything to say?

313
00:15:49.370 --> 00:15:50.870
But little.

314
00:15:50.870 --> 00:15:53.970
I am armed and wellprepared.

315
00:15:53.970 --> 00:15:57.430
Give me your hand,Bassanio.

316
00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.900
Fare you well.

317
00:16:03.430 --> 00:16:07.700
Grieve not that I amfall'n to this for you,

318
00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:12.830
for herein, fortune showsherself more kind than isher custom.

319
00:16:12.830 --> 00:16:16.470
It is still her use to letthe wretched man outlivehis wealth

320
00:16:16.470 --> 00:16:18.370
to view with hollow eyeand wrinkled brow

321
00:16:18.370 --> 00:16:21.100
an age of poverty fromwhich lingering penance

322
00:16:21.100 --> 00:16:22.870
of such misery doth shecut me off.

323
00:16:22.870 --> 00:16:26.970
Commend me to yourhonorable wife.

324
00:16:26.970 --> 00:16:30.100
Tell her the process ofAntonio's end.

325
00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:33.470
Say how I loved you.

326
00:16:33.470 --> 00:16:36.470
Speak me fair in death.

327
00:16:36.470 --> 00:16:38.300
And when the tale is told,

328
00:16:38.300 --> 00:16:41.870
bid her be judge whetherBassanio had not once a love.

329
00:16:41.870 --> 00:16:44.170
Repent but you that youshall lose your friend,

330
00:16:44.170 --> 00:16:47.030
and he repents not that hepays your debt.

331
00:16:47.030 --> 00:16:49.200
For if the Jew do cut butdeep enough,

332
00:16:49.200 --> 00:16:51.900
I'll pay it instantly withall my heart.

333
00:16:51.900 --> 00:16:56.770
Antonio, I am married to awife which is as dear tome as life itself,

334
00:16:56.770 --> 00:16:59.130
but life itself, my wife,and all the world

335
00:16:59.130 --> 00:17:01.870
are not with me esteemedabove thy life.

336
00:17:01.870 --> 00:17:03.870
I would lose all, ay,sacrifice them all

337
00:17:03.870 --> 00:17:06.670
here to this devil, todeliver you.

338
00:17:06.670 --> 00:17:08.700
Your wife would give youlittle thanks for that

339
00:17:08.700 --> 00:17:10.600
if she were by to hear youmake the offer.

340
00:17:10.600 --> 00:17:13.130
I have a wife who Iprotest I love.

341
00:17:13.130 --> 00:17:14.470
I would she were inheaven,

342
00:17:14.470 --> 00:17:18.730
so she could entreat somepower to change thiscurrish Jew.

343
00:17:18.730 --> 00:17:20.570
'Tis well you offer itbehind her back.

344
00:17:20.570 --> 00:17:23.470
The wish would make elsean unquiet house.

345
00:17:23.470 --> 00:17:26.530
These be the Christianhusbands?

346
00:17:28.170 --> 00:17:32.300
I have a daughter.

347
00:17:32.300 --> 00:17:34.830
Would any of the stock ofBarabbas

348
00:17:34.830 --> 00:17:38.330
had been her husbandrather than a Christian.

349
00:17:41.970 --> 00:17:45.000
We trifle time.

350
00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:47.970
I pray thee, pursuesentence.

351
00:17:52.730 --> 00:17:57.100
A pound of that samemerchant's flesh is thine.

352
00:17:57.100 --> 00:18:01.570
The court awards it, andthe law doth give it.

353
00:18:01.570 --> 00:18:04.470
Most rightful judge.

354
00:18:04.470 --> 00:18:06.630
And you must cut thisflesh from off his breast.

355
00:18:06.630 --> 00:18:10.570
The law allows it, and thecourt awards it.

356
00:18:10.570 --> 00:18:12.870
Most learned judge.

357
00:18:15.400 --> 00:18:17.700
A sentence!

358
00:18:28.900 --> 00:18:30.200
Come...

359
00:18:32.770 --> 00:18:34.800
prepare.

360
00:18:51.270 --> 00:18:54.430
Tarry a little; there issomething else.

361
00:18:54.430 --> 00:18:59.200
This bond doth give theehere no jot of blood.

362
00:18:59.470 --> 00:19:03.370
The words expressly are "apound of flesh."

363
00:19:03.370 --> 00:19:05.570
Take then thy bond.

364
00:19:05.570 --> 00:19:08.530
Take thou thy pound offlesh.

365
00:19:08.530 --> 00:19:11.970
But in the cutting of itif thou dost shed one dropof Christian blood,

366
00:19:11.970 --> 00:19:15.800
thy lands and goods are,by the laws of Venice,

367
00:19:15.800 --> 00:19:17.770
confiscate unto the stateof Venice.

368
00:19:17.770 --> 00:19:19.000
Oh, upright judge!

369
00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:20.300
Mark, Jew.

370
00:19:20.300 --> 00:19:21.370
Oh, learned judge.

371
00:19:23.100 --> 00:19:27.470
Is that the law?

372
00:19:27.470 --> 00:19:28.730
Thyself shall see the act.

373
00:19:28.730 --> 00:19:31.100
For, as thou urgestjustice,

374
00:19:31.100 --> 00:19:34.030
be assured thou shalthave justice more thanthou desirest.

375
00:19:34.030 --> 00:19:35.330
Oh, learned judge.

376
00:19:35.330 --> 00:19:37.130
Mark, Jew, a learnedjudge.

377
00:19:40.300 --> 00:19:45.430
I take this offer then.

378
00:19:45.430 --> 00:19:48.270
Pay the bond thrice andlet the Christian go.

379
00:19:48.270 --> 00:19:49.530
Here is the money.

380
00:19:49.530 --> 00:19:51.500
Soft, the Jew shall haveall justice.

381
00:19:51.500 --> 00:19:52.730
Soft, no haste.

382
00:19:52.730 --> 00:19:54.470
He shall have nothing butthe penalty.

383
00:19:54.470 --> 00:19:56.530
Oh, Jew, an upright judge.

384
00:19:56.530 --> 00:19:57.970
A learned judge.

385
00:19:57.970 --> 00:20:01.930
Therefore prepare thee tocut off the flesh.

386
00:20:01.930 --> 00:20:03.170
Shed thou no blood,

387
00:20:03.170 --> 00:20:07.930
nor cut thou less nor morebut just a pound of flesh.

388
00:20:07.930 --> 00:20:10.700
If thou tak'st more orless than just a pound,

389
00:20:10.700 --> 00:20:14.500
be it so much as makes it lightor heavy in the substance

390
00:20:14.500 --> 00:20:17.930
or the division of thetwentieth part of onepoor scruple,

391
00:20:17.930 --> 00:20:21.570
nay, if the scale do turn butin the estimation of a hair,

392
00:20:21.570 --> 00:20:25.800
thou diest, and all thygoods are confiscate.

393
00:20:25.800 --> 00:20:27.100
A second Daniel.

394
00:20:27.100 --> 00:20:28.270
A Daniel, Jew.

395
00:20:28.270 --> 00:20:32.500
Now, infidel, I have youon the hip.

396
00:20:32.500 --> 00:20:34.430
Why doth the Jew pause?

397
00:20:34.430 --> 00:20:35.830
Take thy forfeiture.

398
00:20:54.330 --> 00:20:56.170
Give me my principal andlet me go.

399
00:20:56.170 --> 00:20:57.400
I have it ready for thee.

400
00:20:57.400 --> 00:20:58.570
Here it is.

401
00:20:58.570 --> 00:21:00.170
He hath refused it in theopen court.

402
00:21:00.170 --> 00:21:01.870
He shall have merelyjustice and his bond.

403
00:21:01.870 --> 00:21:04.770
A Daniel still say I, asecond Daniel.

404
00:21:04.770 --> 00:21:06.830
I thank thee, Jew, forteaching me that word.

405
00:21:06.830 --> 00:21:09.670
Shall I not have barely myprincipal?

406
00:21:09.670 --> 00:21:11.500
Thou shalt have nothingbut the forfeiture

407
00:21:11.500 --> 00:21:15.400
to be so taken at thyperil, Jew.

408
00:21:19.100 --> 00:21:23.370
Why then, the devil givehim good of it.

409
00:21:26.700 --> 00:21:29.530
I'll stay no longerquestion.

410
00:21:29.530 --> 00:21:33.770
Tarry, Jew, the law hathyet another hold on you.

411
00:21:36.230 --> 00:21:38.800
It is enacted in the lawsof Venice

412
00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:42.030
if it be proved against analien

413
00:21:42.030 --> 00:21:44.400
that by direct or indirectattempts

414
00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:46.600
he seek the life of anycitizen,

415
00:21:46.600 --> 00:21:49.570
the party 'gainst thewhich he doth contrive

416
00:21:49.570 --> 00:21:51.730
shall seize one half hisgoods.

417
00:21:51.730 --> 00:21:56.000
The other half comes to theprivy coffer of the state.

418
00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:00.830
And the offender's lifelies in the mercy of theDuke only

419
00:22:00.830 --> 00:22:03.170
'gainst all other voice.

420
00:22:05.400 --> 00:22:07.300
In which predicament I saythou stand'st,

421
00:22:07.300 --> 00:22:11.200
for it appears by manifestproceedings

422
00:22:11.200 --> 00:22:14.070
that indirectly, anddirectly too,

423
00:22:14.070 --> 00:22:17.000
thou hast contrivedagainst the very life ofthe defendant,

424
00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:22.000
and thou hast incurred thedanger formerly by merehearsed.

425
00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:25.300
Down therefore, and begmercy of the Duke.

426
00:22:31.670 --> 00:22:35.070
Beg that thou mayst haveleave to hang thyself.

427
00:22:35.070 --> 00:22:37.570
And yet, thy wealth beingforfeit to the state,

428
00:22:37.570 --> 00:22:40.670
thou hast not left thevalue of a cord.

429
00:22:40.670 --> 00:22:45.730
Therefore, thou must behanged at the state's charge.

430
00:22:45.730 --> 00:22:47.830
That thou shalt see thedifference of our spirit,

431
00:22:47.830 --> 00:22:50.370
I pardon thee thy lifebefore thou ask it.

432
00:22:50.370 --> 00:22:55.130
For half thy wealth, it isAntonio's.

433
00:22:55.130 --> 00:22:57.400
The other half comes tothe general state

434
00:22:57.400 --> 00:23:01.770
which humbleness may driveinto a fine.

435
00:23:01.770 --> 00:23:04.030
Ay, for the state, not forAntonio.

436
00:23:04.030 --> 00:23:07.430
Nay, take my life and all.

437
00:23:07.430 --> 00:23:10.070
Pardon not that.

438
00:23:10.070 --> 00:23:13.700
You take my house when youdo take the prop

439
00:23:13.700 --> 00:23:15.700
that doth sustain myhouse.

440
00:23:15.700 --> 00:23:19.600
You take my life when youdo take the means wherebyI live.

441
00:23:19.600 --> 00:23:21.730
What mercy can you renderhim, Antonio?

442
00:23:21.730 --> 00:23:23.030
A halter gratis.

443
00:23:23.030 --> 00:23:24.430
Nothing else, for God'ssake.

444
00:23:24.430 --> 00:23:30.700
So please, my lord, theDuke, and all the court,

445
00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:33.130
to quit the fine for onehalf of his goods,

446
00:23:33.130 --> 00:23:34.470
I am content.

447
00:23:34.470 --> 00:23:37.930
So he will let me have theother half in use,

448
00:23:37.930 --> 00:23:41.700
to render it upon hisdeath unto the gentleman

449
00:23:41.700 --> 00:23:43.230
that lately stole hisdaughter.

450
00:23:43.230 --> 00:23:45.900
Two things provided more:

451
00:23:45.900 --> 00:23:50.330
that for this favor, hepresently become a Christian.

452
00:23:51.630 --> 00:23:53.730
The other, that he dorecord a gift

453
00:23:53.730 --> 00:23:56.470
here in the court of allhe dies possessed

454
00:23:56.470 --> 00:23:59.400
unto his son, Lorenzo, andhis daughter.

455
00:23:59.400 --> 00:24:03.200
He shall do this, or elseI do recant

456
00:24:03.200 --> 00:24:06.700
the pardon I latepronounced here.

457
00:24:06.700 --> 00:24:07.870
Art thou contented, Jew?

458
00:24:07.870 --> 00:24:09.000
What dost thou say?

459
00:24:17.830 --> 00:24:20.200
I am content.

460
00:24:23.330 --> 00:24:25.930
Clerk, draw a deed ofgift.

461
00:24:57.130 --> 00:25:03.170
I pray you, give me leaveto go from hence.

462
00:25:08.370 --> 00:25:10.130
I am not well.

463
00:25:12.600 --> 00:25:15.800
Send the deed after me,and I will sign it.

464
00:25:17.200 --> 00:25:19.930
Get thee gone, but do it.

465
00:25:31.730 --> 00:25:35.430
In christening, thou shalthave two godfathers.

466
00:25:35.430 --> 00:25:37.400
Had I been judge, thoushouldst have had ten more

467
00:25:37.400 --> 00:25:40.900
to bring thee to thegallows, not to the font.

468
00:25:45.430 --> 00:25:50.700
Sir, I entreat you homewith me to dinner.

469
00:25:50.700 --> 00:25:53.130
I humbly do desire yourgrace of pardon.

470
00:25:53.130 --> 00:25:55.830
I must away this nighttoward Padua,

471
00:25:55.830 --> 00:25:57.930
and it is meet I presentlyset forth.

472
00:25:57.930 --> 00:26:01.170
I am sorry that yourleisure serves you not.

473
00:26:03.570 --> 00:26:09.970
Antonio, gratify thisgentleman,

474
00:26:09.970 --> 00:26:14.970
for in my mind, you aremuch bound to him.

475
00:26:20.670 --> 00:26:25.270
Most worthy gentleman, Iand my friend have, byyour wisdom,

476
00:26:25.270 --> 00:26:27.900
been this day acquitted ofgrievous penalties.

477
00:26:27.900 --> 00:26:31.370
in lieu whereof 3,000ducats, due unto the Jew,

478
00:26:31.370 --> 00:26:34.000
we freely cope yourcourteous pains withal.

479
00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:36.100
And stand indebted, overand above,

480
00:26:36.100 --> 00:26:38.730
in love and service to youevermore.

481
00:26:38.730 --> 00:26:40.930
He is well paid that iswell satisfied.

482
00:26:40.930 --> 00:26:43.630
And I, delivering you, amsatisfied

483
00:26:43.630 --> 00:26:45.430
and therein do accountmyself well paid.

484
00:26:45.430 --> 00:26:47.270
My mind was never yet moremercenary.

485
00:26:47.270 --> 00:26:50.330
I pray you know me when wemeet again.

486
00:26:50.330 --> 00:26:52.000
I wish you well, so I takemy leave.

487
00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:55.070
Dear sir, of force I mustattempt you further.

488
00:26:55.070 --> 00:26:58.630
Take some remembrance of usas a tribute, not as fee.

489
00:26:58.630 --> 00:27:00.500
Grant me two things, Ipray:

490
00:27:00.500 --> 00:27:03.200
not to deny me, and topardon me.

491
00:27:03.200 --> 00:27:07.100
You press me far, andtherefore I will yield.

492
00:27:07.100 --> 00:27:08.370
Give me your gloves.

493
00:27:08.370 --> 00:27:10.370
I'll wear them for yoursake.

494
00:27:10.370 --> 00:27:14.200
And for your love, I'lltake this ring from you.

495
00:27:14.200 --> 00:27:15.630
Do not draw back yourhand.

496
00:27:15.630 --> 00:27:18.500
I'll take no more, and you,in love, cannot deny me this.

497
00:27:18.500 --> 00:27:20.770
This ring, good sir?

498
00:27:20.770 --> 00:27:22.270
Alack, it is a trifle.

499
00:27:22.270 --> 00:27:24.130
I will not shame myself togive you this.

500
00:27:24.130 --> 00:27:25.830
I will have nothing elsebut only this.

501
00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:27.530
And now methinks I have amind to it.

502
00:27:27.530 --> 00:27:29.730
There's more depends onthis than on the value.

503
00:27:29.730 --> 00:27:32.900
The dearest ring in Venicewill I give you

504
00:27:32.900 --> 00:27:34.630
and find it out byproclamation.

505
00:27:34.630 --> 00:27:37.270
Only for this, I pray youpardon me.

506
00:27:37.270 --> 00:27:38.930
I see, sir, you areliberal in offers.

507
00:27:38.930 --> 00:27:41.800
You taught me first to beg,and now methinks you teach me

508
00:27:41.800 --> 00:27:43.230
how a beggar should beanswered.

509
00:27:43.230 --> 00:27:46.570
This ring, good sir, wasgiven me by my wife.

510
00:27:46.570 --> 00:27:49.000
And when she put it on,she made me vow

511
00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:53.030
I should neither sell norlose nor give it.

512
00:27:53.030 --> 00:27:56.070
That 'scuse serves manymen to save their gifts,

513
00:27:56.070 --> 00:27:57.900
and if your wife be not amadwoman

514
00:27:57.900 --> 00:28:00.230
and know how well I havedeserved this ring,

515
00:28:00.230 --> 00:28:04.330
she would not hold outenemy forever for givingit to me.

516
00:28:04.330 --> 00:28:06.330
Well, peace be with you.

517
00:28:08.100 --> 00:28:11.100
My lord, Bassanio, let himhave the ring.

518
00:28:11.100 --> 00:28:12.870
Let his deserving, and mylove withal

519
00:28:12.870 --> 00:28:15.430
be valued 'gainst yourwife's commandment.

520
00:28:34.970 --> 00:28:38.170
Go, Gratiano, run andovertake him.

521
00:28:38.170 --> 00:28:39.470
Give him the ring.

522
00:28:39.470 --> 00:28:41.570
Bring him, if thou canst,unto Antonio's house.

523
00:28:41.570 --> 00:28:44.300
Away, make haste.

524
00:28:46.130 --> 00:28:49.600
Come, you and I willthither presently,

525
00:28:49.600 --> 00:28:52.900
and in the morning early, wewill both fly toward Belmont.

526
00:28:52.900 --> 00:28:56.330
Come, Antonio.

527
00:29:07.400 --> 00:29:08.700
Inquire the Jew's houseout.

528
00:29:08.700 --> 00:29:10.800
Give him this deed; lethim sign it.

529
00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:13.470
We'll away tonight and be aday before our husbands home.

530
00:29:13.470 --> 00:29:15.730
This deed will be wellwelcome to Lorenzo.

531
00:29:15.730 --> 00:29:16.800
Fair sir!

532
00:29:18.230 --> 00:29:20.300
You are well o'erta'en.

533
00:29:20.300 --> 00:29:22.970
My lord, Bassanio, uponmore advice,

534
00:29:22.970 --> 00:29:24.930
hath sent you here thisring

535
00:29:24.930 --> 00:29:27.100
and doth entreat yourcompany at dinner.

536
00:29:27.100 --> 00:29:29.030
That cannot be.

537
00:29:29.030 --> 00:29:33.370
His ring I do accept mostthankfully, and so I prayyou tell him.

538
00:29:33.370 --> 00:29:36.070
Furthermore, I pray youshow my youth oldShylock's house.

539
00:29:36.070 --> 00:29:37.570
That will I do.

540
00:29:37.570 --> 00:29:40.870
Sir, I would speak withyou.

541
00:29:40.870 --> 00:29:43.670
I'll see if I can get myhusband's ring,

542
00:29:43.670 --> 00:29:45.870
which I did make him swearto keep forever.

543
00:29:45.870 --> 00:29:47.270
Thou mayst, I warrant.

544
00:29:47.270 --> 00:29:49.600
We shall have old swearing

545
00:29:49.600 --> 00:29:51.630
that they did give therings away to men.

546
00:29:51.630 --> 00:29:53.630
But we'll outface them andoutswear them too.

547
00:29:53.630 --> 00:29:55.630
Away, make haste.

548
00:29:55.630 --> 00:29:58.670
Thou know'st where I willtarry.

549
00:29:58.670 --> 00:30:01.100
Come, good sir, will youshow me to this house?

